    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_92193373" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/92193373" />
    <a title="Jamie Collins" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/321673-jamie-collins"><img alt="Jamie Collins" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1450191045p2/321673.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/92193373?book_show_action=true">Mar 02, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jamie Collins" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jamie Collins" href="/user/show/321673-jamie-collins">Jamie Collins</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/321673-jamie-collins?shelf=historical-mystery">historical-mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/321673-jamie-collins?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer92193373" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1687090236191074104">I really enjoyed this. It&apos;s very nice historical fiction and a pretty good mystery as well. Hambly&apos;s writing is excellent. The characterizations are rich and achingly realistic. She does tend (so it seems to me, after reading three of her novels) to indulge in outrageous action scenes for her endings.<br/><br/>Benjamin January is the titular free man of color, and at the end I was insufficiently convinced of his need to remain in the hazardous environment of 1833 New Orleans rather than return to Europe, </span>
  <span id="freeText1687090236191074104" style="display:none">I really enjoyed this. It's very nice historical fiction and a pretty good mystery as well. Hambly's writing is excellent. The characterizations are rich and achingly realistic. She does tend (so it seems to me, after reading three of her novels) to indulge in outrageous action scenes for her endings.<br /><br />Benjamin January is the titular free man of color, and at the end I was insufficiently convinced of his need to remain in the hazardous environment of 1833 New Orleans rather than return to Europe, where he has been living for years and where, if he wasn't exactly considered a first class citizen, he was at least in no danger of being kidnapped and sold into slavery, or being flogged for being "impudent" to a white man.<br /><br />There's a murder and a mystery, but the novel is mostly concerned with an examination of the intricate French-flavored society in which the white and mixed-race citizens of New Orleans mingle, and where there exists a safe zone for persons of African ancestry that is threatened by the encroachment of Americans and their "custom" of enslaving anyone with dark skin.<br /><br />There were a lot of French names to keep track of. I would have appreciated a dramatis personae.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1687090236191074104" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


