<div id="review_3659891034" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3659891034" />
    <a title="Nancy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1731678-nancy"><img alt="Nancy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1235348588p2/1731678.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3659891034?book_show_action=true">Nov 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nancy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nancy" href="/user/show/1731678-nancy">Nancy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3659891034" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9158705235809042045">I read a lot of books like this--somewhere between three and four stars. My usual mental dividing line: would I read another book by this author? I do plan to try another Barbara Hambly book in the Benjamin January series--I&apos;ll explain why in a minute--so this, then, should be a four-minus. But there are things about the books that the author will have to fix. In other words, this book had some real drawbacks. If she settles into the character, the setting and the plots, it could be a really rew</span>
  <span id="freeText9158705235809042045" style="display:none">I read a lot of books like this--somewhere between three and four stars. My usual mental dividing line: would I read another book by this author? I do plan to try another Barbara Hambly book in the Benjamin January series--I'll explain why in a minute--so this, then, should be a four-minus. But there are things about the books that the author will have to fix. In other words, this book had some real drawbacks. If she settles into the character, the setting and the plots, it could be a really rewarding series--and the first book in any series is often the weakest. <br /><br />The main character, Ben January, is rather wonderful. He's a musician (bonus!) and a physician, a free man of color in a totally unique place and time in American history--1830s New Orleans, where 'Americans' were crude, backcountry white Kentuckians and White Creoles (French and Spanish) were the ruling class. Reading the book sent me to the French-English dictionary and Google about three dozen times--was this *really* what it was like? Evidently, yes. A piece of history I never knew, one that fits into my new understanding of caste, based on skin color, and layers of almost incomprehensible biases and rules. At least four stars for this part.<br /><br />There are, however, some significant flaws. First, Hambly is one of those authors who make you pay for all her research, by including every single (interesting/irrelevant) factoid. Languages, costumes, street names, foods, superstitions, architectural details--all the customs of the country and a whole lot more that clutters up the narrative and makes you lose the train of the plot. <br /><br />Sometimes, it's colorful, but often, it's downright confusing. There are SO many characters, some of which are totally unnecessary to the plot. Worse, the story begins at a masked ball, and characters are identified by the costume they're wearing--and later, Hambly scrambles the costumes with the characters' actual names (which are largely in French), leading to lots of page flipping (if you have pages) or just reading on if you're reading it on a Kindle, hoping you'll remember who the purple pirate was. If, indeed, he is at all important. Hambly also has a bad habit of overwriting--the book is a festival of adjectives.<br /><br />The mystery is eventually unraveled, but unevenly laid out. The surrounding environment is much more interesting--and once you get over your anger at how people come to accept inequity, prejudice and social mores, becomes an interesting framework for another story. I'll try, try again. In the meantime, three-plus.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9158705235809042045" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

